 <exercises>
		<title>Activities</title>
		
		<exercise>
		<title>Analyzing the Equation of Motion</title>
		<statement>
		<p>Looking at equation <xref ref="pendulumE2"></xref> apply the small-angle approximation to determine an equation of motion. Then determine the oscillation frequency of the simple pendulum. </p>
		</statement>
		<answer>
		<p> Applying the small-angle approximation you find that <m> \sin\theta \approx \theta</m> and the equation of motion becomes,
		
		<men> \frac{d^2}{dt^2}\theta(t)=-\frac{g}{L} \theta(t)</men>
from this and your model of simple harmonic motion, you can directly see that the oscillation frequency is
		
		<men> \omega_p = \sqrt{\frac{g}{L}}</men>.
		
		</p>
		</answer>
		</exercise>
